    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Ledebouria minima are tincture, infusion, tea, salve, and ointment. A tincture is a concentrated liquid solution of the plant's bioactive compounds, typically extracted in ethanol or glycerin, used for medicinal purposes. The infusion is a liquid extract obtained by steeping the plant's leaves in hot water, while tea is a more diluted version, often consumed for its putative health benefits. A salve is a topical preparation of Ledebouria minima, usually in the form of a gel or paste, applied to the skin to treat localized conditions, while an ointment is a thicker, more viscous substance used for similar purposes. These preparations are used to exploit the plant's bioactive compounds, such as alkaloids and saponins, which are reported to possess anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties.",
